<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1616,2037]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,1689,1713]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a posthumous homage to the first author’s father, Roosevelt Machado, in recognition for his great human quality and love.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1616,2037]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1760,1785]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[343,563,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Anoreina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roosevelti">
<emphasis box="[343,563,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Anoreina roosevelti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[579,661,1760,1784]" captionStart="FIGURES 96 – 101. 96" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1945,1968]" captionTargetBox="[218,1263,202,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 96 – 101. 96, Anoreina helenae sp. nov. holotype male; 97, Anoreina roosevelti sp. nov. holotype male; 98, Anoreina triangularis (Martins &amp; Galileo, 2005) holotype female, dorsal habitus; 99, ventral habitus; 100, fifth urosternite showing the longitudinal glabrous band; 101, labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/207500/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[632,661,1760,1784]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="97.0">97</number>
</figureCitation>
) differs from all other species of the genus in having the frons without erect setae near the inner margin of the lower eye lobe, having the lower eye lobe about twice as wide as the upper lobe, having the anterior margin of the prothorax distinctly sinuous, having the elytra with a large, median, irregular band of yellowish pubescence bordered by whitish and dark brown pubescence, and having the elytral apices obliquely truncate.
</paragraph>
